This stage-based limitation resulted in characters typically moving only laterally, rarely approaching or retreating from the camera. This is exemplified in "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), where actors enter from stage right and move horizontally across the frame, with the camera remaining stationary even when they exit the frame.

The frontal proscenium composition naturally led to the predominance of long shots and occasional medium shots. Notably, close-up shots are entirely absent from the Edison catalog's trick films. This approach mirrors theatrical presentation, where audiences view the entire performance within the stage's boundaries. Following theatrical convention, performers rarely approached the camera, precluding the possibility of close-ups.

Typically, early trick films adhered to a one-conceptual-shot-equals-one-film format. This constrained most films to approximately one minute or less, depending on the frame rate. It also limited their narrative scope, with most focusing on brief vaudeville-style illusions such as magic tricks, disappearances, and transformations rather than developed stories. Importantly, while viewers perceived one continuous shot, the technical execution often involved multiple shots seamlessly combined to create illusions. This is evident in "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), where careful observation reveals the transition point where the shot with the severed "head" begins, though the film appears as one continuous take to viewers.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" represents, both in essence and name, an "oxymoron of 'Old-New'" as Ian Watt explains in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic style has experienced both condemnation and praise, facing accusations of superficiality while simultaneously being celebrated for its evocation of the 'terrible sublime' (Burke). Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, considered the original Gothic novel, merged elements from both "ancient and modern" romances to pioneer the Gothic genre and establish a new form of literary expression. Walpole combines "traditional" theatrical elements with 'modern' natural mimicry to create what he terms "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4).

The Gothic genre draws heavily from medieval gothic theater, architecture, and customs. Even when The Castle of Otranto was first published, the term "gothic" had already been applied to various peoples, styles, and historical periods. It was often viewed as outdated or unsophisticated compared to "modern" social and literary "developments." What has enabled Gothic literature to endure and remain simultaneously antiquated yet fresh to readers far removed from its original context is its unique combination of theatrical "Gothic" elements with the novel's innovative format, which offers intimate insight into character psychology.

The concept of Chivalry stands as one of the most significant gothic elements in these novels. In The Castle of Otranto, the medieval notion of chivalry and knightly training is both preserved and transformed. Gothic writers, particularly Walpole, emphasized chivalry because it represented an ideal - the archetypal knight embodying bravery, honor, and competence - which they perceived as lacking in their contemporary society. Through the incorporation of chivalric ideals and customs, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized, foreshadowing Gothic literature's evolution into Romanticism, while serving as a mirror for contemporary improvement. Walpole, writing during politically turbulent times and facing personal difficulties, may have believed that the moral integrity and inherent "goodness" associated with the gothic era had somehow diminished in his contemporary society. This perspective is evident in several characters, particularly Frederic, who embodies numerous chivalric traits and is portrayed through traditional knightly imagery as a suffering prince, supposedly martyred by infidels. The portrayal of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is deliberately exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management represents the sequence of processes involved in moving goods from customer order through raw materials, supply, production, and product distribution to the customer. The term "supply chain management" was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. He described the comprehensive process of planning, implementing, and controlling supply chain operations to satisfy customer needs quickly and efficiently. A supply chain consists of six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these six key elements to deliver optimal customer service.

Production serves as the initial and foundational step in the supply chain process. It defines when, why, where, and how everything will be manufactured. Managers must understand customer desires, primarily by analyzing market demands - the most significant indicator of customer needs. Once management has assessed market demands and determined product specifications and quantities, they select optimal production facilities based on volume capabilities and quality standards, while ensuring customer satisfaction requirements are met. The next phase involves scheduling workloads and equipment maintenance. Production represents a critical supply chain component where every detail matters; inadequate planning could result in significant time and financial losses. For instance, from my experience at Walmart and Target, these retailers maintain detailed protocols for every business aspect, from employee dress codes to shipment receiving procedures. Such structured processes ensure smooth operations without directional confusion or unclear expectations.

The second key element, supply, involves making strategic decisions about facility core capabilities and determining appropriate outsourcing partnerships. A single product may involve multiple production divisions, each with distinct equipment, workforce, and specializations. Managers must determine the most suitable division for different product processes. They may also opt for outsourcing to external companies, primarily to achieve velocity - the ability to maintain quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low operational costs.

Victorian novels are distinguished by their overwhelming attention to detail and their focus on the period's aristocracy. Two novels that are considered Victorian but deviate from this tradition are "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights". Both novels employ elements of mystery and an inclination toward the bizarre, unusual for novels of this period, which strengthens the characters in each work and provides insights into their motivations and emotions.

"And now swarms of confusing and bewildering thoughts flooded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing furiously: for their words echoed in his ears; and when he regained his own awareness... he found himself speaking to them.... Suddenly, he recoiled at the sound of gunfire; loud screams and shouts arose; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything was noise and chaos, as an invisible hand hurriedly led him away. Through all these rapid visions ran an undefined, uncomfortable sensation of pain that tormented him ceaselessly."

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary school students. I did my best to help them in any subject they struggled with, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the teachers recruited me to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having significant difficulties with reading. I realized something wasn't right; he was having the most unusual problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others he couldn't pronounce at all - it was very strange. He was of Latino descent, I was certain of that, but the boy spoke perfect English.

The situation continued until I met his mother. I was watching over a few remaining students while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother came in. She didn't speak any English, only Spanish. With my limited Spanish knowledge (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. That's when it hit me like a thunderbolt: Adrian could read just fine, he simply wasn't familiar with the English alphabet. I'm not sure if this realization helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issue in schools, particularly in California. It also shows that these problems aren't always as obvious as we might think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still be a major obstacle. While everyone acknowledges this problem exists, what's the solution? In Adrian's case, it was relatively straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is far more complex. There's no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, ESL classes - none of these alone will solve the problem. The key is combining all these approaches!

The dual language system, in particular, is an excellent concept - not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. Research shows that children in two-way bilingual education programs often outperform their peers academically. While some fear this approach wastes resources or won't benefit the majority of students, that's incorrect. If we implemented these programs as the standard rather than the exception, all children would benefit. How do we accomplish this? Should we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and impractical. However, there's no reason we can't have special aides or tutors who are bilingual.

From childhood on, most of us are told that there is something greater than ourselves, greater than we can comprehend. Some of us are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to temple or search within themselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down to us by our parents. Some, however, reject them completely, denying that there could be anything beyond knowing in our own egocentric universe. We might adopt one value system, only to later change our minds and replace it with another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our own unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us from the shadows into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof above while smoking our cigarettes together. The gutters channeled the rain down, flooding the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain with a look that seemed half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner in recent months, his clothes hanging loosely on his frame. His hair had thinned too, sparser than I remembered. He continued staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, frightened, and unable to tell my father how much I would miss him because talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the falling rain in the June twilight.

My father died that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation hadn't eased his suffering but had kept him alive a few months beyond the doctors' predictions; I couldn't determine the value of this when it merely meant he suffered longer. What kind of God would do this, I wondered. Alone in the night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I thought, He had long since stopped listening to me.

I hadn't wanted to watch him transition from this life to another. So I didn't. I couldn't bear to watch the life that created me while it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived rather than how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family did, and knew Dad wouldn't want his only child to be a witness to his death. I curled up in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of republicanism. Although he was primarily a farmer, this profession combined with his brief political career created a man known for his commitment and candor in matters of personal liberty and governance. His devotion to an agricultural system formed the foundation for virtually all his views on government. His effort to preserve and promote what he considered the most noble of all professions shaped his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

He believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to create an ideal system, as there were no established traditions to constrain the nation's founders, enabling the creation of genuine self-governance. He held strong convictions about natural human rights, believing them to be interconnected—if one right was denied, all would ultimately fail, diminishing the value of those remaining. These rights, he maintained, should be beyond government interference.

Taylor believed that an effective government must account for humanity's inherent capacity for both good and evil. He maintained strict views on moral dualism, asserting that since government is administered by humans, all its virtues and vices must be human in nature. He identified good principles as those protecting private property, advancing agriculture, and limiting capitalism, believing that a government founded on sound principles would function fairly regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by self-interest and greed.

As a dedicated Republican of his era, Taylor advocated for strict constitutional interpretation, favoring a severely limited federal government with powers explicitly outlined in the Constitution. He recognized that an expansive federal government would be costly and prone to despotism. However, he cautioned against overly literal interpretation, believing that understanding the founders' intent was crucial to prevent corruption. Notably, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the nation's true charter, as it more clearly depicted the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single unified nation.

I gazed downward, my mind barely processing the scene before me. With detached precision and practiced awareness, I analyzed what lay before my eyes, refusing to connect it to any deeper understanding. Thoughts flickered through my consciousness, appearing and vanishing almost instantaneously. My mind worked with such fluid efficiency that it seemed I wasn't truly thinking, but rather experiencing a pure, liquid awareness of what I observed.

Once, following an artist's recommendation, I bought an instructional book titled "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." Since age six, I'd longed to learn drawing, and this book covered everything from basic pencil handling to the brain's methods of processing lines. One key technique involved placing a frame around the subject matter, transforming complex scenes - like a fruit bowl in a kitchen connected to a dining room - into manageable compositions, such as simply a bowl of fruit on a plane.

In that moment, staring at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally construct such an artistic frame. I stood transfixed, overwhelmed with wonder. While Picasso had his Blue Period, Monet his gardens, and Renaissance masters their spectrum of colors, if I dared consider my perspective artistic, this would be my beginning - my "Work in Brown."

My fingers found their artistic tool, muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, my intentions taking physical form in what could have been my most creative moment. Water swirled serenely, crystal clear. Particles broke free, drifting into nothingness. With increasing urgency, my hand struck the toilet handle again. The stubborn brown mass remained unmoved, clinging like a slug to the bowl's bottom.

Standing there in my green tie, feet planted apart, holding a mop loosely, I frowned at the crude deposit of processed organic matter - someone's special delivery for the unfortunate bathroom cleaners at Rite Aid. After several more flushes and moments of contemplation, my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping itself until it resembled a makeshift glove. Standing straight before bending at the waist, I lowered my hand into the bowl, not unlike a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are losing their lives while driving. Multiple factors contribute to this deadly statistical trend among America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health point out that one aspect of the problem is that the adolescent brain is literally unprepared for driving's dangers. Lack of experience is also central to the issue. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and running off the road.

Young people are particularly at risk when traveling with peers—something that anyone with common sense knows happens regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted research showing a clear correlation between passenger age and accident frequency.

California and other states have attempted to enhance teen driver safety through provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit underage passengers.

However, provisional licenses are, in my view, merely temporary solutions. The fundamental issue is that younger drivers, as a group, are simply not capable of adequately handling the risks and responsibilities, according to all statistical indicators. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a standard driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research indicates a common tendency among those under 19-20 to seek thrills purely for the sensation. Therefore, it makes sense to delay driving until at least after this thrill-seeking tendency has begun to diminish.

This paper examines three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, it provides a concise definition of the disorder. Subsequently, it explains the diagnostic process, including common characteristics or "warning signs." The paper concludes by discussing ways classroom teachers can support students with CAPD in mainstream educational settings.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), describes how effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. In its specific definition, it refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the underlying neurobiological activity that generates electrophysiological auditory potentials. Simply put, it's a disorder where the brain cannot properly process heard information. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing capabilities and aren't considered hearing impaired; rather, the brain regions responsible for translating auditory input, distinguishing words, or separating conversation from background noise don't function typically.

The disorder's earliest documentation dates to the mid-1950s, when it was termed "auditory imperception" during studies of children with communication disorders. Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari pioneered testing methods in 1954, followed by Kimura's introduction of dichotic testing in 1961, which explained the physiology of auditory perception. A significant national conference in 1977 sparked increased research into childhood CAPD.

CAPD presents various symptoms: difficulty localizing sounds in space, problems distinguishing between multiple sound events, inability to recognize sound patterns, challenges in detecting speech variations (such as identifying sarcasm through voice changes), auditory masking where one sound blocks another, difficulties in synthesizing sound information meaningfully, and problems processing the sequence of auditory information.

Diagnosis requires systematic evaluation of listening behavior and performance on auditory function tests, conducted by professionals including audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists. The assessment may involve questionnaires, behavioral observations, and response monitoring to various stimuli. Currently, there's no single, universally effective diagnostic tool, and the disorder's cause remains unknown. Many diagnostic procedures involve testing the patient's ability to differentiate between simultaneous auditory stimuli, while advanced methods include measuring acoustic responses within the ear.

In pursuing my studies in social work, I aim to establish a career with the Department of Family and Children's Services to assist abused or neglected children and support troubled families. The values I can bring to social work include: service, respect, ethical conduct, dedication to improving relationships between others, and commitment to my own professional development to maintain competence in my field. These core values are not just important for social workers; they hold deep personal significance for me.

I had always felt drawn to helping others, but was uncertain about my career direction. During my high school and college years, I observed many individuals avoiding their problems through denial or using less-than-ideal coping mechanisms. These observations led me to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still uncertain about my path after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I took some time off. That summer, I encountered a sixteen-year-old boy at a friend's house, seeking refuge from abusive parents. When I learned he had contacted the police, I visited his parents' home to offer assistance. After explaining my psychology background to the officers, they asked me to speak with the parents since legal intervention wasn't possible. The parents appeared nervous, dismissing their son's actions as "manipulative" and minimizing family conflicts as "simple disputes." This experience crystallized my interest in social work, particularly in helping children navigate these so-called "simple" family disputes.

Social justice represents another crucial value in social work. While our society claims to value individuality and mourns lost lives, we often follow outdated traditions rather than embracing true uniqueness. If we genuinely mourn lost individuals, why do we pressure ourselves to conform? As someone who values individuality, I've actively protested social injustice throughout my academic years - through unconventional hair colors, authentic self-expression in clothing, multiple ear piercings, openly supporting GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and confronting racism and discrimination whenever encountered. My commitment to social justice remains unwavering, and I will continue to stand against social inequities.

This paper examines the biological and sociocultural models as they relate to the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model emphasizes inherited genetic information and medical health aspects, while the sociocultural models examine environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia analyzes these models and elaborates on selected research to better explain and relate to these models. The research findings and their explanations are then evaluated to highlight their specific strengths and limitations.

Sleep disorders can be classified as primary sleep disorders, sleep disorders associated with other mental disorders, or sleep disorders related to other conditions. Primary sleep disorders are categorized as either Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while sleep disorders related to other mental disorders are connected to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Additional sleep disorder categories may result from medical complications or substance use. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia involves difficulties in achieving or maintaining sleep, Primary Hypersomnia presents as difficulty maintaining wakefulness, both persisting for at least one month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. Whereas Dyssomnias concern sleep initiation and maintenance, Parasomnias are sleep disorders characterized by behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological events during sleep.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genetic factors, hereditary elements, and physiologically acquired aspects. Research has shown that hypothalamic neurons containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness cycles. Studies with mice have identified phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons that specifically control sleep/wake states. The findings suggest potential implications for human sleep regulation and disorder treatment, highlighting both genetic and environmental influences on sleep mechanisms.

I've been studying at University Park for approximately two and a half years now, spanning four and a half semesters. Getting around campus poses a challenge for many students, myself included. During my freshman year, I was assigned to a dorm in East Halls - practically at the eastern edge of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. The journey from my residence in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard Building near campus center could take up to 25 minutes on foot, particularly during State College's frequently adverse weather conditions.

In conversation with a recent alumnus, I discovered that not long ago, East Halls was separated from the main campus by vast undeveloped areas. Today, those spaces have been transformed with athletic fields, major new structures including the new Creamery and health services building, and are now surrounded by apartment complexes. As our campus continues its expansion, transportation between locations becomes increasingly challenging. What's the optimal solution to this mobility issue? On a university campus, the answer lies in bicycles. However, bikes alone aren't the complete solution - students need to utilize them, and the campus infrastructure must be designed to accommodate cyclists.

I recently spoke with a friend who had returned to cycling after several years away from it. He expressed surprise at ever having stopped, saying, "Bikes are fantastic - there was a period when cycling wasn't considered cool, but it's really the most practical way to get around." Beyond its health benefits, cycling represents the most efficient mode of transportation. A simple breakfast and some physical effort can carry you over 30 miles. Like many upperclassmen, I now reside off-campus, at a distance comparable to some dormitories from the campus center. Purchasing a bicycle has been my most prudent decision this year. My daily classes in Thomas Building would normally require a twenty-five-minute walk from my residence, but cycling reduces this to just 5 minutes at a good pace. The only drawback is that Pollock Road, while offering the most direct route to Thomas Building, can be challenging to navigate, whether on foot or by bike. While walking has its merits, my schedule simply doesn't allow for it. Without my bicycle, walking would be my only dependable option for reaching classes. Walking to Thomas Building daily would consume an additional 30-40 minutes - that's over two and a half hours weekly. Factor in all other walking time for various classes and appointments, and it amounts to more time than I can afford to spend.

Aldous Huxley critiques the dual threats of technology and capitalistic structures through his creation of a dystopia in Brave New World. In this world, collective identity supersedes individuality, and citizens are conditioned from birth to prioritize instant gratification above all else. These citizens are revealed to be mere pieces in a greater scheme, confined within an ideology dictated by the World Controller. When analyzed through a Marxist theoretical framework, the author's underlying concerns about these developing systems become apparent. Common Marxist concepts such as homogeneity and reification strengthen the argument that Huxley's novel serves as commentary on the flaws in his era's emerging economic system.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness, wherein the general population is prevented from understanding their true economic relationship with other classes, being primarily focused on personal gain. This results from ideological control of the working class, clearly demonstrated through the conditioning of citizens in Brave New World. The lower classes (Delta, Gamma, etc.) lack genuine free will; through hypnopaedia, their drive to consume, spend, and indulge is artificially enhanced. This manipulation is orchestrated by the World Controller, exemplifying hegemony - the complete domination of social classes by a controlling group. The lower classes remain oblivious to this manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that perpetuates the system. While upper classes are born with the potential for awareness, few Alphas or Betas besides characters like Bernard take any action against it, instead accepting their designated roles. The interactions between social classes serve as powerful indicators of capitalism's perceived oppression.

Genuine interpersonal relationships are notably absent in Brave New World. Characters, even major ones, lack psychological depth - perhaps Huxley's suggestion that the combination of technology and capitalism strips humanity of authentic free will and expression. Love and extreme emotions are non-existent; instead, interactions remain superficial, evidenced by men's focus on women's physical attributes and women's casual discussion of their encounters. Moreover, each social class's acceptance of their hierarchical position reflects capitalism's socioeconomic impact. Their unwavering adherence to community roles mirrors Marxist observations about the proletariat, who are falsely convinced of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to peer expectations.

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in an Islamic studies course at CBC. One of the main topics of heated debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever before. Looking back at events since 9/11, I have personally witnessed mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance toward Islam in America. I don't think we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with his obvious Muslim family background, back in 2001.

The Prophet's Biography fascinates me because, based on my understanding of Muhammad's history, the biography contradicts what I know of his personality. From my previous knowledge and studies, I had understood that Muhammad forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and compelling them to adopt the Islamic faith. However, the biography portrays him as something of a martyr, misunderstood by others, who demonstrated humility. According to this account, people gradually recognized the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

There are also remarkable parallels between Jesus's ministry and Muhammad's 'miracles.' The most striking example is the story of him multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men abundantly. This writing style suggests to me that the authors wanted to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove himself but simply lived in truth and miracles. This approach particularly troubles me as it seems to diminish Jesus Christ's miracles and life, almost as if they're attempting to appropriate Jesus's characteristics through Muhammad.

The biography contains numerous accounts that appear designed to provide 'witness testimony' or examples of people who 'independently' converted to Islam. However, these stories often come from third-hand sources - accounts of someone who heard from someone else who heard from another person. Rather than strengthening the credibility of these stories, I found this pattern made them less convincing and more suspicious.

What disturbs me most about this work is its attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, endearing, wise, and gentle man. Historical accounts seem to contradict this portrayal of Muhammad as gentle and humble, and I wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the true historical circumstances of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and convictions of Jesus during his lifetime were quickly abandoned in the evolution of Christian thinking that followed his death. Looking at this history in broad terms, we can observe Christianity's continuous drift from its origins. Today's world demonstrates an increasing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendencies. While traditionally-minded people remain and will resist thinking beyond their learned beliefs, this segment of the population may not be influential enough to shape the whole.

Among Christians, historical consciousness will grow tremendously in the years to come. A desire will emerge to separate later Christian doctrinal additions from the original intentions of the religion's founder. Though it may take generations or centuries, the outcome appears inevitable: A great reversal in Christian historical trends will occur, leading back to its original form. A movement will grow that systematically removes layers of doctrine, as if turning back time, until only Jesus's original divine message to humanity remains, stripped of later interpretations.

When this movement sweeps through the United States and Europe, inspiring masses to worship as in Jesus's time, following only his teachings, the church as an institution will remain strong as a guiding force. However, as theological understanding reverts, the extreme diversity within Christianity will consolidate into greater uniformity of belief and practice. Instead of differences between regions, denominations, and divisions, we will see increasing similarities.

Human history is full of such reversals - consider how Christians, once persecuted by the Roman Empire, later saw that empire become Christian, or how our nation moved from enslaving African-Americans to having African-American leadership. This coming religious reversion will unfold within Christianity, unraveling history in search of its source, while reducing diversity. Crucial to this process will be an understanding of Jesus's words as metaphorical rather than literal.

Looking back far enough, we find only Judaism as Christianity's theological foundation. Monotheism, the concept of divine revelation, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion when Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 BCE. The Jewish population was not unified but divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" demonstrates how humans are inherently greedy and self-centered at their core. They only want to take care of themselves and make their lives as comfortable as possible, while never concerning themselves with those beneath them. "The Jungle" illustrates this in numerous ways. The most obvious example can be found in the owners and managers of the large factories. Their sole desire is to make their companies and factories as large and impressive as possible. They show no regard for anyone or anything that stands in their way or gets harmed by their progress. According to Upton Sinclair's work, the industrial landscape dominated the sky with its stark buildings and towering chimneys, spewing endless streams of smoke into the distance. Sinclair paints a vivid picture of the environmental devastation being created. He reveals that the owners have absolutely no consideration for any person or animal that might suffer harm. They remain indifferent to the massive clouds of smoke billowing from their factories or the animal waste running off from the countless pens throughout Packingtown.

The owners and managers showed equal disregard for the workers who made them wealthy. They would take any measure to increase or save money, creating an environment where "loyalty and decency were sacrificed for profit." Workers faced brutal hours and could be dismissed without notice, receiving neither compensation nor assistance in finding new employment. During this period, there were few if any laws protecting workers' safety or welfare. This allowed management to operate unchecked, forcing employees to increase productivity while working in deplorable conditions. Though never explicitly stated, those who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were simply expected to endure these horrific conditions, both in the factories and in their surrounding environment. No agencies or organizations existed to support or inform the working class. While labor unions formed, they often caused more harm than good, profiting from the very workers they claimed to represent. The workers were so severely mistreated and trapped within Packingtown's system that they were effectively described as slaves, existing at the mercy of men as brutal and unscrupulous as any slave driver of the past.

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-declared superior poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain that the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. While Virgil certainly used this term, there is a more contemporary source that deserves recognition. Poe had a strong interest in German authors.

This reference is significant as it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. In his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," Karl J. Arndt discusses the similarities between their two poems, concluding that Poe was emulating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned author of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts - the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within Faust's second part lies a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. Following her death, he drinks heavily and weeps remembering his dead queen. Deciding his time has come, he bequeaths all his possessions to his children except for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, casts the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The King of Thule's disposition and the king's portrayal in Dream-Land bear striking similarities, perhaps representing a dark mirror of Poe's own loss and reliance on alcohol.

Poe mentions Thule twice in his collected works: once as "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land," where it serves as bookends to the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces, with the speaker in "Dream-Land" describing Thule's landscape as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, in a colorless, shadowed world. These scenes parallel "The King of Thule," where the protagonist has lost his wife, experiences profound loneliness, and loses his will to rule or live. The entire poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's work.

Goethe was an influential author whom Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. Beyond this connection, Poe would have encountered Goethe's work through the numerous reproductions that followed the original publication.

Under California law, a customer who sustained injuries from slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store might be entitled to punitive damages if it can be demonstrated that the store manager acted with malice by failing to address a reported spill for thirty minutes while eating dinner, despite being notified twice.

A judge would likely allow Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages to proceed. To justify punitive damages, plaintiffs must demonstrate that the defendant acted with willful and conscious disregard for probable harmful consequences, while also proving the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have anticipated the likely harm from an uncleaned spill, given multiple previous customer injuries at D&D. While her argument about the despicable nature of Martin's actions may be less compelling, it remains reasonable considering the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and Martin's subsequent failure to maintain store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed manager Paul Martin about an applesauce spill. Martin, who was on his dinner break, dismissed the concern, stating he "didn't have time for customer complaints." At 5:15 PM, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, reported the same spill, receiving an identical response. At 5:30 PM, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill, suffering a serious back injury. The store had already documented five slip-and-fall incidents that year. Palmer is now pursuing both compensatory and punitive damages, and we're evaluating whether to file for partial summary judgment against the punitive damages claim.

Under California Civil Code § 3294(a), punitive damages may be awarded in non-contractual cases where the defendant demonstrated "oppression, fraud or malice." The statute defines malicious conduct as either intentionally harmful or, lacking direct intent, "despicable" and showing "willful and conscious disregard for others' rights or safety." Courts have found malice when defendants consciously disregarded plaintiffs' rights, particularly when they recognized potential dangerous consequences yet willfully failed to prevent them.

She had always sensed something was missing in her life. It was an unfulfillable longing that haunted her. It began when she was around 14, just entering her teenage years, and persisted three years later at age 17. By then, she had realized she was searching for someone rather than something. Yet she felt no attraction to any boys. Some had been drawn to her, making awkward attempts to court the uncourtable, but no one captured her interest.

She often questioned this peculiar situation, trying to understand what could cause such an unusual circumstance in a teenage girl. Years of reflection had produced theories, but none satisfactory enough to seriously consider. So she continued living, constantly examining her desires.

Life at home was typically peaceful. Her parents were gentle, balanced people who never quarreled with each other and rarely argued with their daughter. Their only conflicts arose from her assertions of independence and free spirit. Though born to serene parents, she balanced their calm nature with her vibrant and engaging personality, making her well-liked, especially given her inherent kindness.

Today, however, was different. As she wandered from room to room, seeking fresh inspiration, she heard her mother's beautiful voice release a sharp scream from the kitchen. She rushed in, panic rising as she called out, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother on the floor, clearly in pain, breathing shallow "ow"s. Her mother managed to say between gasps, "Honey... I... need you to take me... to the hospital." Her daughter knelt beside her, asking, "Where can I lift you?" At that moment, she was deeply grateful for her strength training classes as she carefully carried her mother to the car, laying her across the back seat before driving away.

The hospital visit brought its typical mix of antiseptic smells and illness, tinged with anxiety. But she noticed none of this, focused entirely on helping her mother. She carried her in swiftly, calling for medical assistance. Concerned staff quickly gathered, transferring her mother onto a gurney. As they wheeled her away for immediate examination, her daughter was left alone with her worry.

It had all happened because her mother had fallen from a stepstool while reaching for a vase in the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternative Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," correlates with a lower risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet represents a modified version of the Mediterranean diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but incorporating fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (in comparison to saturated fats) and fish, while reducing intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have documented an inverse relationship between Mediterranean diet adherence and overall cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, while an intervention trial demonstrated the Mediterranean diet's superiority over a low-fat diet in achieving weight loss and improving the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Earlier studies had not specifically addressed stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological investigation followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, with no prior history of CVD or diabetes, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study encompassing 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Between 1984 and 2004, researchers calculated an aMed diet score six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year study period. FFQs underwent validation studies, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through medical records, hospital documentation, autopsies, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were designated as "probable" and included, accounting for approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions.

To minimize random individual variation and better represent long-term dietary patterns, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated. The study accounted for potential confounding factors by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone replacement therapy, multivitamin use, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

The findings revealed that greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with reduced risk of both CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up period, researchers documented 2,391 incident cases of CHD, 1,763 incident cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths. Women in the highest aMed quintile demonstrated a significantly lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign reads "Hitler lives in Burma."

Ellen Page, the Juno star, stands alone at a street corner, holding a cardboard sign above her head with this disturbing message scrawled in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation controlled by a despotic military junta that seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, the country witnessed its first public demonstrations in ten years. These protests, led by numerous Burmese monks and dubbed "The Saffron Revolution" after their traditional robe color, began peacefully. While the government initially tolerated the monks' gatherings, the situation soon deteriorated into what many described as open warfare between the monastics and military regime, with forces raiding monasteries nationwide. Foreign journalists faced immediate arrest, and Japanese photographer Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27th, 2007, merely for documenting a protest. Though official figures cite 13 deaths, defected Colonel Hla Win revealed, "The true death toll reaches thousands, far beyond what's been reported."

Such oppression is hardly unprecedented. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, Japanese emperors were considered divine beings, and our current president, George W. Bush, maintains close ties with Ted Haggard, who leads an organization of conservative ideologues.

Notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where students, intellectuals, and workers challenged authoritarian rule. Death toll estimates vary dramatically, from the government's claim of 200-300 to the Chinese Red Cross's estimate of 2,000-3,000. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s saw Hutu militias, backed by their government, systematically eliminating Tutsis and political moderates regardless of ethnicity. Hitler's Third Reich, which spanned years and nations, systematically persecuted and murdered Jewish people, standing as another extreme example of state-sponsored brutality.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz stems largely from his longevity and consequently his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While Ellington's presence at the piano remains subtle in many of the compositions chosen for this assignment, his brilliance as a composer shone through in creating rich and intricate pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. Ellington masterfully crafted frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also writing tightly orchestrated passages that leveraged the distinctive styles of band members to emphasize musical ideas. In doing so, he enhanced the overall orchestral tone, creating unique and cohesive sounds tailored to each piece. His profound understanding of each player's individual sound, combined with his ability to blend these elements within an expanding ensemble, enabled him to compose some of jazz history's most groundbreaking and brilliant works.

The Grove Music dictionary notes Ellington's sonic innovation, particularly referencing Creole Love Call as an example of his pioneering use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This early work exemplifies Ellington's technique of using vocals to add texture and color without being constrained by lyrics...

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D'Arcy Thompson noted in 1917 that "even now zoologists have barely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," the same holds true today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk shell formation through both individual development and evolutionary history.

Our research examines how mathematical modeling of developmental and evolutionary changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help illuminate the mechanisms involved in the direction and scale of evolutionary-developmental changes. We utilized X-ray images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that could be used to model both theoretical and actual shell morphologies. These parameters were input into the CerioShell software program. We created models of hypothetical shell shapes to understand the boundaries of possible morphological variation in Prunum. These findings are being integrated with experimental and observational studies to better comprehend macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be understood as a tube-like structure that travels through 360 degrees of space over time. These spiral turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which rotate around an imaginary central axis. This axis extends through the shell's central column, known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls expand can vary, and they are separated by a continuous line called the suture. In most shells, the final whorl (body whorl) is the largest. The spire comprises all whorls except the last one. The apex marks the spire's tip, while the opposite end is the base. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be examined from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. The standard orientation shows the shell in an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.

To count whorls, one should view the shell from above and locate where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn to divide the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and can be measured to the nearest quarter whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. The aperture's path can be traced using coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and its horizontal and vertical radii. This trajectory can be represented both graphically and mathematically, allowing for parameter variation and modification of mollusk shell formation models.

The infant and child mortality rate in Indonesia has remained relatively constant over the past decade. While the country is making progress toward achieving many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the improvement rates for child and maternal health fall far short of the necessary advances needed to reach their goals by 2015. The various reasons for these deficiencies are discussed below and indicate the need to strengthen the healthcare system rather than focusing on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has shown progress in increasing the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional practitioners, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions in cases of complicated pregnancies (explaining the high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). In essence, the improvements shown in this particular indicator are somewhat deceptive, and substantial work remains to be done. Furthermore, there has been a decrease in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five being treated by healthcare professionals. While postnatal care data is incomplete, it's evident that this area is also problematic, with low rates throughout the country.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, at approximately 4%. These rates also highlight another concerning disparity: while urban areas show a 7% c-section rate, rural areas only show 2%. This underscores the issue of inequitable healthcare coverage across the country. Healthcare services are clearly concentrated in urban areas. Another access issue relates to vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles. The poor evidently face greater difficulties accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to most effectively address the service gap. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing exclusively on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches to address the above issues are appealing, as they offer more targeted, manageable objectives and typically generate faster results, there are notable drawbacks. One significant disadvantage is that heavy investment in programming for one particular health sector often results in reduced funding for other areas, with human resources gravitating toward better-funded sectors (as exemplified by international HIV/AIDS funding's impact on family planning). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs leads to service duplication and lack of coordination, resulting in increased paperwork for supplies and funding.

The categorization of popular music has expanded so dramatically over the last century that it now encompasses such a vast array of genres that creating a definitive list has become nearly impossible. Adding to this complexity, most if not all genres—including rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, to name just a few—have developed numerous sub-genres and even further subdivisions within their domains.

Heavy Metal rock, in particular, has arguably evolved into one of popular music's most diverse and expressive genres over the past four decades. Its expressiveness stems from its ability to convey a wide spectrum of emotions, though it tends to gravitate toward darker themes. Its diversity emerged shortly after the genre's inception, as artists began to recognize and exploit its inherent flexibility, creating distinct sub-genres that continued to branch into further variations, a process that continues to this day.

In the contemporary heavy metal landscape, we've reached a point where the sheer number of specialized niches makes it challenging to precisely define what constitutes heavy metal. While it has incorporated elements from numerous other genres, it's essential to trace its origins. To truly comprehend today's ubiquitous metal music, one must understand both the metal movement itself and why it transcends mere genre classification to qualify as a cultural movement.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement characterized by darkness. It can be viewed as a "music of excess"—greater bass, increased volume, heightened violence, and enhanced theatricality. Rather than embracing primitivism, it demands technical proficiency; metal musicians are known for their instrumental mastery, which is evident in their compositions. The movement was significantly influenced by the psychedelic drug culture of the mid-1970s, leading to increasingly experimental, otherworldly recordings. It introduced visceral, dark qualities that were largely absent from mainstream popular music, and later generations of metal drew inspiration from the dark, intense characteristics reminiscent of the Romantic Era.

Several decades before the Surrealist artists began creating their dream-like works, the artist Henri Rousseau was shaping his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. "The Dream," a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, depicts not only a woman overwhelmed by the wonders of the land she visits in a dream but also represents Rousseau's own personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. From the beginning of his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art enthusiasts, finding himself faced with a difficult internal dilemma in pursuing this goal. "The Dream" is Henri Rousseau's work that best reflects his lifelong internal struggle: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance from the critical art world he so admired, or to allow himself to develop creatively independent and unique, forging his own path as he went along.

Many great thinkers have proposed an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this connection. As John Keats expresses in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all you know on earth, and all you need to know." Much of our life's knowledge comes through education or experience. Yet, as Keats suggests, our appreciation of ethics and aesthetics seems to develop without these conventional teaching methods.

Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are largely attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature moves us, or why an action is moral, rather than providing rigid rules for judging or creating good art or ethical behavior.

More fundamentally, critical analysis of art or morality can never fully capture the essence of goodness or beauty. While we might discuss the Mona Lisa in terms of technique, composition, or cultural context, these elements alone don't explain its artistic merit. People often preface their analysis of favorite artworks or literature with "There's just something about it" before delving into more detailed explanations. I believe both art and morality resist complete reduction to their constituent qualities. As Flannery O'Connor notes, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Something transcendent remains beyond even the most thorough analysis of literature, and I believe ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein observes, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This ineffable quality, this je ne sais quoi, represents the most powerful attribute of both art and morality, creating a bridge between them.

I believe morality and art are so deeply connected because we experience both most profoundly at a noumenal level, to use Kant's terminology. They affect us in ways we can experience but never fully explain. This connection strengthens particularly in literature. As McKean observes, literature's distinctive feature is its moral quality. While moral standards might not apply to all arts, such as music, they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living inherently involves values, and literature's significance lies precisely in the values we discover within it.

Today's Germany is regarded as a powerful force, a unified nation with its own unique cultural blend stretching from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This same culture can be experienced from Cologne on the Rhine, through central Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given such a distinctive culture, it's not surprising that the Germany we know today emerged from various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the German people. The origin of its name is heavily debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe then known as the Tungrians, who had previously been called Germans before crossing the Rhine and engaging in battle with Gallic forces. Julius Caesar first used the word "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and fought against Germanic tribes who often crossed the Rhine under dubious pretenses. He adopted this word from the Gauls themselves and used it to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not.

The play "Twelfth Night" appears to suggest that while disguise can be useful for prolonged deception, one must ultimately shed this new identity to avoid the risk of losing oneself in the process. A significant challenge in ending a deception is the potential for alienation. Ultimately, one must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others. For while some may react neutrally to discovering they've been deceived, others will not take it so lightly and will likely feel offended by the entire masquerade.

The theme of deception through gender role reversal is particularly problematic as it raises many peripheral questions, with perhaps the most crucial being "why?" Why does the individual feel compelled to abandon their own identity and adopt a disguise as the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it's clearly a form of self-protection: "I'll take you to a captain in this town, where my maiden garments lie, through whose kind help I was preserved to serve this noble count..."

The matter of gender-based deception proves especially complex in the play, as it forces characters to confront unexpected emotions and attractions. This is particularly evident in the cases of Olivia and Orsino, whose reactions to Viola/Cesario reveal deeper questions about the nature of attraction and identity. While modern readers might find progressive undertones in this exploration, Shakespeare seems to use these complications more as a commentary on the superficiality of judgment based on appearances, as demonstrated by Olivia's quick transition from pursuing Cesario to accepting Sebastian, and ultimately embracing Viola as family rather than a romantic interest.

German colonial rule has been recognized by various observers for its brutality, particularly regarding the genocide of the Herero and Nama people in German South West Africa. Naturally, such a vast colonial empire cannot be characterized by such a simple description. The German colonial empire exhibited as much diversity in its policies and governance style as it did in its geography. Educational provisions across the colonies showed similar variation. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a substantial population of educated and literate Africans. German educational initiatives in Cameroon and other colonies also received praise from contemporary writers.

The situation in South West Africa (modern-day Namibia) stood in marked contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and took a leading role in native education, in South West Africa the responsibility for educating the indigenous population was delegated almost entirely to missionary societies, which received minimal government support. The government did, however, invest considerable resources in European education in the colony, establishing state schools and providing stronger support and oversight for missionary schools serving the white population. These educational policies had lasting implications for South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies could boast significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to South West Africa's divergent experience. This study aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors, with particular emphasis on new research regarding settler and colonial authority attitudes toward native Africans.

There exists extensive literature on education in the German colonial empire. Most sources are in German and date from the early twentieth century, during or shortly after German colonial rule. Early works primarily sought to describe the educational systems in these colonies. Later English-language scholarship expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education across German colonies and more detailed analysis of specific educational aspects. These studies revealed significant variations in colonial educational systems. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa stands as the most notable work directly addressing this paper's topic. Cohen's comparative analysis of the two colonies' educational systems explores the factors behind their differences, attributing many of South West Africa's distinctive educational characteristics to its large settler population.

Compared to Germany's other colonial territories, South West Africa enjoyed a relatively temperate climate, despite much of its territory being arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these comparatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, while East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population, had only 5,336 white inhabitants.

The United States of America and Mexico exemplify two nations that were once characterized by a lasting rivalry spanning 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The pinnacle of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States defeated Mexico and acquired Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two nations, finally subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry originated as Americans and Mexicans clashed over fundamental issues including religion, culture, and tradition, alongside significant material interests.

This pattern mirrors many other nations experiencing enduring rivalries with their neighbors. Countries sharing borders typically face conflicting interests that contribute to the development of rival positions. The United States-Mexico relationship reflects a common pattern seen in enduring rivalries between neighboring nations. According to David M. Pletcher (1977), "Only Mexico and Cuba presented long-lasting overarching diplomatic challenges for America" (p. 41). Indeed, both nations' geographic proximity to the United States contributed to their rival status, while other Latin American nations maintained positive relations with the United States.

Religious differences created a division between the two nations, a common historical phenomenon. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that "while twentieth-century Americans opposed fascism and communism, their eighteenth and nineteenth-century counterparts opposed Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). Similar to how the Cold War rivalry between the United States and Soviet Union combined ideological differences with competition over vital interests, this earlier conflict centered on religious rather than political ideologies. This mistrust evolved from historical English-Spanish antagonism, with both nations inheriting prejudices from their colonial predecessors, significantly hampering the development of friendly diplomatic relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most conflicts during this period involved territorial issues, particularly border raids and frontier problems. Bandit and outlaw attacks on American border towns remained problematic until both nations established military presence along their borders.

According to Schmitt (1974), the rivalry began to diminish as "Mexico became increasingly economically dependent on the United States" and ultimately concluded when American priorities "shifted from territorial expansion to economic involvement in Mexico" during the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply rooted need for safety and security that I lacked as a child. "You'll always find work; people will always be sick" was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I grew through adolescence and beyond. So - although my dream was to be a scientist or journalist - preferably both - I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old, single, with practically no savings and unable to work. To this day I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I literally have nothing left I can call my own. I get by, but each day is a struggle that challenges my security, safety, and self-worth. While nothing in my life is certain anymore, one thing remains undeniably true: I couldn't have survived all these years without the support of my family and a few good friends, regardless of how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that life will always bring emergencies - both large and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well-prepared one is, some challenges are simply too great to overcome alone.

I completely agree that we in the U.S. need to stop placing all our trust in big government's "basket" - heaven knows it's deteriorating and falling apart anyway. However, I'd much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again - learning to help each other and ask for help - rather than each of us individually rushing to build our own backyard fallout shelters.

American Conservatives speak of the "rugged individualism" that built this country, but in reality, what sustained our ancestors through hard times wasn't rugged individualism - it was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't reach the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting with duct tape for windows in case of a biological attack. I have multiple flashlights, various batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to preserve your own food - do it. It's an excellent idea, as is having a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're doing all this, make sure to get to know your neighbors.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly attachments and achieved enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism—with its most orthodox branch known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion, now approximately twenty-five centuries old, appears quite different today than it did during Buddha's lifetime. This transformation is evident everywhere, exemplified in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where an annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance despite never being mentioned in Buddha's original teachings. These variations span from surface-level traditions to the soteriological essence of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has needed to adapt its doctrinal principles over time. This evolution can be attributed to various forces, both external and internal, hostile and benign.

Several key terms require definition for this discussion. The concept of internal versus external forces is crucial: internal forces emerge from within the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status, while external forces come from non-Buddhist sources. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, stemming from negative perceptions of Buddhism. Benign forces neither intend to help nor harm the Buddhist community, though they may inadvertently do either. These distinctions will be important throughout our discussion.

To understand these changes, we must first examine the fundamental doctrines at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is primarily contained within the Tripitaka—the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the discourses, the Vinaya Pitaka holds the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka encompasses Buddhism's metaphysical aspects. These metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no-self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Understanding these concepts is essential for ending Sansara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. With the end of Sansara comes the cessation of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) through enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka establishes life guidelines: five precepts for laypeople (abstaining from killing, lying, stealing, sexual misconduct, and intoxicants), while monks follow numerous additional rules. At Buddhism's doctrinal core lie the four noble truths, beginning with Dukkha (the truth of suffering), followed by the truth that attachment causes suffering, and that suffering can be overcome.
